Analogically, 
$$
v=u^{mn}z+x^{m-1}F^{m}(x,u)+mx^{m-2}F^{m-1}(x,u)yu^n+\ldots+mF(x,u)y^{m-1}u^{mn-n}
$$
is linear in $z$. So, if $v=v_1v_2$, then we can assume that $v_1$ does not depend on $z$. Therefore, $v_1\mid u^{mn}$. Since $u$ is irreducible, we can assume $v_1=u^{d}$ for some $d$. But since $v=v_1v_2$ and $v_1$ does not depend on $z$,  we have 
$$
v_1\mid x^{m-1}F^{m}(x,u)+mx^{m-2}F^{m-1}(x,u)yu^n+\ldots+mF(x,u)y^{m-1}u^{mn-n}. 
$$
If $d>0$, then we obtain $u\mid  x^{m-1}F^{m}(x,u)$. This contradicts to the condition $F(x,0)\neq const$. Hence, $d=0$ and $v_1=const$.


If $D$ is not irreducible, then all elements of its image are divisible either by $u$ or by $v$.
let us prove that $w$ is not divisible by $u$ and $v$. Indeed, $w=xF(x,u)+yu^n$. Since $F(x,0)$ is not a constant and $p(x)$ is not divisible by $u=xz-y^m$, $w$ is not divisible by $u$. Assume $v\mid w$. We have $v=\frac{u^{mn+1}+w^m}{x}$, hence $u^{mn+1}=xv-w^m$ is divisible by $v$. A contradiction. Therefore, $w$ is not divisible by~$v$.
We have 
$$
D(x)=D\left(\frac{u^{mn+1}+w^m}{v} \right)=\frac{mw^{m-1}(-u^nv)}{v}=-mw^{m-1}u^n.
$$
That is $v$ does not divide $D(x)$.

$$
D(y)=D\left(\frac{w-xF(x,u)}{u^n} \right)=-v+\frac{\partial (xF(x,u))}{\partial x}(mw^{m-1}u^n).
$$
This implies that $u$ does not divide $D(y)$. So, $D$ is irreducible.























